            <!-- Explanations -->
            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this loan comparison calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you compare up to four loans at once. For each
                loan, we assume a fixed interest rate and level monthly payments
                until the balance reaches zero. We then add any upfront and
                ongoing fees to show the true cost of borrowing.
              </p>

              <h3>Monthly payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                For a loan with principal \(P\), monthly interest rate \(r\)
                (annual rate divided by 12), and number of monthly payments
                \(n\), the standard payment is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{Payment} = P \times \dfrac{r(1 + r)^n}{(1 + r)^n - 1}
                \)
              </div>
              <p>
                If the interest rate is 0%, the payment is simply \(P / n\).
              </p>

              <h3>What we calculate for each loan</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Standard monthly payment</strong> – the payment needed
                  to pay off the loan in exactly the chosen term, ignoring extra
                  principal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monthly payment including extras &amp; fees</strong> –
                  standard payment plus any extra principal and monthly fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total interest</strong> – sum of all interest charges
                  over the life of the loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total fees</strong> – upfront fees plus all ongoing
                  fees over the life of the loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total cost</strong> – total interest + total fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Effective APR</strong> – the internal rate of return
                  (IRR) on the full cash flow, including fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time to pay off with extra payments</strong> – how
                  long it takes to clear the loan if you add extra principal
                  each month.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest saved vs. no extra</strong> – how much
                  interest you avoid by making extra payments.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How we estimate effective APR</h3>
              <p>
                To compute the effective APR, we treat the loan as a cash-flow
                problem:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  At month 0, you receive the loan amount minus any upfront
                  fees.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Each month, you pay the scheduled payment plus ongoing fees.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                We then solve for the monthly rate \(i\) that makes the net
                present value (NPV) of all cash flows equal to zero:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( 0 = CF_0 + \dfrac{CF_1}{(1 + i)^1} + \dfrac{CF_2}{(1 + i)^2}
                + \dots + \dfrac{CF_n}{(1 + i)^n} \)
              </div>
              <p>The effective APR is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{APR}_\text{eff} = (1 + i)^{12} - 1 \)
              </div>

              <h2>How to compare loans intelligently</h2>
              <h3>1. Look beyond the monthly payment</h3>
              <p>
                A lower monthly payment often just means a longer term. That can
                increase the total interest you pay. Use the
                <strong>total cost</strong> and
                <strong>effective APR</strong> rows to see which loan is truly
                cheaper.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Consider fees as part of the rate</h3>
              <p>
                Two loans with the same interest rate can have very different
                total costs if one has higher upfront or ongoing fees. The
                effective APR captures this difference and is usually the best
                single number for comparison.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Use extra payments to your advantage</h3>
              <p>
                Even small extra principal payments can significantly reduce
                both the payoff time and total interest. Try entering different
                extra amounts to see how much interest you could save.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Match the term to your goals</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Shorter term</strong> – higher payments, but much less
                  interest and faster payoff.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Longer term</strong> – lower payments, but more total
                  interest and higher total cost.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The right choice depends on your budget and risk tolerance. This
                calculator helps you see the trade-offs clearly.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes a fixed interest rate and fixed monthly payments for
                  the full term.
                </li>
                <li>Assumes all fees are known and entered correctly.</li>
                <li>
                  Assumes you keep the loan to maturity (no early payoff or
                  refinancing), except for the extra-payment scenario you
                  specify.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not model variable-rate loans, interest-only periods, or
                  balloon payments.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For complex loan products, use this tool as an approximation and
                always review the lender’s official disclosures.
              </p>
            </section>

